Getting the Materials

Find the Github Repository

  • Google: pritamdalal github

  • click on the first search result

  • click on Repositories

  • click the repository called mfm_python_jumpstart

  • find the green Clone or Download button
    • then select Download ZIP

  • unzip this file and put it on your Desktop

Installing the Anacoda Distribution

How to Install

  • Google: anaconda distribution

  • click on the first search result

  • download the 3.7 version for your platform (Windows, MacOSX)

  • follow the installation instructions

This is our main priority for today, so please let me know if you have questions.

JupyterLab

Launching JupyterLab

  • find and start the Anaconda Navigator application

  • click the Launch button for JupyterLab

  • locate the Github repository folder you downloaded in the file explorer of JupyterLab

  • double click jump_start_tutorial.ipyn

Now we are going to work through the tutorial in JupyterLab.

How to Learn More

Python in the MFM

FM 5091-5092 (Chris Prouty) - the core programming sequence in the MFM program. Python is one of the primary languages covered.

FM 5032 - Volatility Module (Pritam Dalal) - an experiential learning module where we dive deep into machine learning in the context of volatility analysis.

FM 5990 (Pritam Dalal) - an introduction to financial data analysis where we cover pandas, Jupyter, visualization, and machine learning from the ground up.

Books (pdfs in Github repository)

Python Data Science Handbook by Jake Vanderplas - succinct overview of data analysis, visualization, and machine learning in Python.

Python for Finance by Yves Hilpisch - a great treatment of using Python in a variety of quantitative finance contexts.

Python for Data Analysis by Wes McKinney - a comprehensive treatment of Pandas, written by its creator, but it is a bit boring. Probably better as a reference than reading start to finish.

Data Science from Scratch by Joel Grus - builds up a lot of machine learning algorithms from scratch, which is different than how sklearn is often taught.

Automate the Boring Stuff by Al Sweigert - a well written introduction that teaches Python as a general programming language - focuses on automating workflows.

Master of Financial Mathematics (MFM)

Were Pretty Cool

The Master of Financial Mathematics is a professional graduate program offered through the School of Mathematics at the University of Minnesota.

The course work is highly applied, and teaches you the mathematics and programming you need to be at the cutting edge of quantitative finance.

Our goal is for you to be highly effective and highly employable.

Full time students can complete the program in two years. All courses are in the evenings, so this is a great program for working professionals as well.

If you have an interest in mathematics and want to apply in the world of finance and business, then check us out.

What Youll Learn

Derivative Pricing - modern quantitative finance began with the creation of the Black-Scholes option pricing model. We start there and bring you all the way to the cutting edge.

Optimization, Linear Algebra, Statistics - these are the mathematical foundations that drive everything from portfolio construction to neural networks.

Python - build custom modules, packages, applications, and perform machine learning.
